icsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/fix_reading_20260328.mp3 )=
  | WATCH VIDEO ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DeQpOGHZcZDQ )=0A=0AIt=
=E2=80=99s not even an inability to critically think.=0A=0AIt=E2=80=99s an =
inability to read sentences.=0A=0A=E2=80=94 Jessica Hooten Wilson ( https:/=
/fortune.com/2026/01/09/gen-z-college-students-struggling-to-read-professor=
s-forced-to-rethink-standards-warn-of-anxiety-lack-of-workplace-prepardness=
/ )=0A=0AWhen it comes to reading, there is something of a moral panic afoo=
t. In the United States, high-school reading scores are tanking =E2=80=
=A6 and everyone seems to know why.=0A=0ARaised on a diet of internet slop,=
 today=E2=80=99s kids think that =E2=80=98reading=E2=80=99 means scanning t=
he captions of a Tik Tok video. For them, books are becoming incomprehensib=
le relics of a waning literate age ( https://jmarriott.substack.com/p/the-d=
awn-of-the-post-literate-society-aa1 ) . In short, literacy is being murder=
ed, and the killer is the smartphone in every child=E2=80=99s hand.=0A=0AOr=
 is it?=0A=0AIn this essay, I explore a different story about why kids are =
becoming less literate. It=E2=80=99s not a story about kids getting dumbed =
down by an addictive new technology. It=E2=80=99s a story about how adults =
decided to not teach kids how to use a piece of very old technology.=0A=0AL=
et me set the stage with a brief parable.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopd=
own.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/divider.png=0A=0ASeveral millennia ago, =
humans invented ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_writing )  a cle=
ver three-step algorithm for encrypting messages. In step one, the user tak=
es a message and decomposes it into a set of distinct sounds. In step two, =
the user encrypts these sounds into a set of visual symbols. And in step th=
ree, the user preserves these symbols on a physical medium.=0A=0AThe purpos=
e of this encryption technology is to transmit meaning across time and spac=
e. When another user encounters the encrypted message, they decrypt it by e=
mploying the same algorithm in reverse. First, they parse the symbols and c=
onvert them into sounds. Next, they parse these sounds and group them into =
chunks of meaning. Finally, they interpret the decoded message.=0A=0AWith t=
his ancient technology in mind, here is how our story unfolds. For centurie=
s after its invention, the encryption algorithm was used by a small class o=
f administrators who hoarded its secrets. Then, about three hundred years a=
go, the decryption keys were gradually released ( https://ourworldindata.or=
g/literacy )  to the wider population. Eventually, all children received ma=
ndatory decryption training ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compulsory_educ=
ation ) .=0A=0ABut then a funny thing happened. After several generations o=
f formal training, some users began to feel that the decryption algorithm w=
as =E2=80=98natural=E2=80=99, and that its intricacies need not be taught. =
These users created a new approach to training ( https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Whole_language )  whereby the decryption algorithm was learned through =
exposure. New users were shown encrypted messages with convenient pictures =
and cues that elucidated the meaning. The idea was that through repeated ex=
posure, new users would master the technology.=0A=0AOr not.=0A=0AAfter seve=
ral decades of this new learning regime, scientists found that decryption s=
kills were in decline, and that the drop was biggest among the weakest decr=
ypters. Meanwhile, new communication technology had proliferated, leading t=
o confusion about the loss of decryption skill. Was the new technology to b=
lame? Or was it something else? Opinions flared, but conclusive evidence wa=
s in short supply.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/2023/03/divider.png=0A=0AExiting our parable, let=E2=80=99s take stock.=
 In English, the act of encrypting a message is called writing. And the act=
 of decrypting it is called reading. Both acts rely on an implicit algorith=
m for decomposing linguistic meaning into sounds, and encoding these sounds=
 into symbols. Good readers have mastered this algorithm. Bad readers have =
not. And today, bad readers have not mastered this algorithm largely becaus=
e they were not taught how it works. Or at least, that is my contention her=
e.=0A=0AThe backstory is that in the 1980s and 1990s, a movement called the=
 =E2=80=98whole language=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whole_lan=
guage )  approach to reading swept through anglophone schools. According to=
 this new zeitgeist, learning to read was as =E2=80=98natural=E2=80=99 as l=
earning to speak. It was a skill that could be learned largely by exposure.=
 Soon this method of =E2=80=98vibe-based literacy=E2=80=99 ( https://www.ne=
wyorker.com/news/annals-of-education/the-rise-and-fall-of-vibes-based-liter=
acy )  came to dominate elementary-school pedagogy, with devastating result=
s. Yes, some students flourished. But a large portion of kids were simply l=
eft behind, destined to be perpetually poor readers. Today, we are living w=
ith the consequences.=0A=0AIn this essay, I make the case that the modern d=
ecline of high-school reading ability is in large part, due to the spread o=
f whole-language methods. I will build my case in three parts.=0A=0AIn Part=
 I, I review how reading scores have declined among US high-school students=
. I show how this decline is not uniform, but is instead marked by a wideni=
ng skill gap. Among US high-school students, the best readers have actually=
