t=E2=80=99s not something that government surveys measure.=0A=0AIn Part II,=
 I take a detour into the history of how writing was invented. My purpose i=
s to illustrate exactly why reading is hard to learn, and why students bene=
fit when the requisite skills are explicitly taught. Then I discuss the who=
le-language movement to not teach these skills =E2=80=94 a movement based o=
n a misguided view of what it means to read.=0A=0AIn Part III, I build the =
case that whole-language instruction is the main cause of the widening read=
ing-score gap. I survey many lines of evidence, perhaps the most important =
of which is that the reading-score gap can be reversed =E2=80=A6 by abandon=
ing whole-language methods and teaching structured literacy.=0A=0AOf course=
, my goal here is not to exonerate smartphones and other screen devices fro=
m wasting kids=E2=80=99 time. Instead, my point is that if we don=E2=80=
=99t properly teach kids how to read, they have little chance of actually d=
oing it.=0A=0APart I: The decline of high-school reading ability=0A=0AOur s=
tory begins with a much-discussed piece of evidence. Among US high-school s=
