=0A=0APart II: Why reading is hard to learn=0A=0AIn literate cultures, writ=
ing is so ubiquitous that few people realize that it is a form of technolog=
y, and a miraculous one at that. Writing is an ingenious technique for encr=
ypting spoken language into visual symbols =E2=80=94 symbols that can then =
be decrypted by another person.=0A=0AThe advantages of writing over speakin=
g are profound. A spoken sentence is gone the moment it is uttered. A writt=
en sentence can be preserved indefinitely. A spoken sentence requires a liv=
ing speaker. A written sentence can be read long after the writer is dead, =
and in places the writer never imagined. In short, reading and writing come=
 with many advantages over spoken language. But they also have one big down=
side, which is that compared to speaking, learning to read and write is far=
 more difficult.=0A=0AThere=E2=80=99s a reason for this difficulty =
=E2=80=94 a reason that every grade-school teacher should have plastered on=
 their wall. As the linguist Mark Liberman observes ( https://www.ling.upen=
n.edu/courses/Fall_2003/ling001/reading_writing.html ) , reading is hard to=
 learn =E2=80=9Cfor the same reasons that writing was hard to invent=
=E2=80=9D. The lesson here is that each time a child struggles to read, the=
y are replicating, in shortened form, humanity=E2=80=99s lengthy struggle t=
o invent the written word.=0A=0ATo get a sense for this formative struggle,=
 realize that humans developed spoken language as early as 135,000 years ag=
o ( https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.=
2025.1503900/full ) . Yet formal writing dates back a mere 5,000 years ( ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_writing ) . Now, I say =E2=80=98form=
al=E2=80=99 writing, because long before humans encoded words into abstract=
 symbols, we drew pictures that conveyed meaning. For example, more than 40=
,000 years ago, humans in present-day Spain drew a picture of a bull ( http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cave_of_El_Castillo )  that is instantly recogniz=
able to anyone today. It is with such pictures that writing begins ( https:=
//www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2520385123 ) .=0A=0AFor the first proto-wri=
ters, the most obvious way to encode meaning was to draw an image of the th=
ing they had in mind. To elicit the idea of a bull, they drew a bull. To el=
icit the idea of a snake, they drew a snake. And so on. Now, the intriguing=
 part is that even today, drawing pictures remains the most obvious way to =
encode meaning.=0A=0AFor example, if you show a toddler a picture of a snak=
e, they=E2=80=99ll happily shout =E2=80=98snake=E2=80=99. Indeed, using thi=
s image-based method, a toddler will happily decrypt the meaning of pictogr=
aphs that are thousands of years old. (See Figure=C2=A013 ( https://economi=
csfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-c=
ase-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-hieroglyphics )  for some ancient =
Egyptian examples.1 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-ki=
ds-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#f=
n1 ) ) But note what the toddler will not do. When shown the word =E2=80=
=98snake=E2=80=99, the toddler will not shout =E2=80=98snake=E2=80=99. And =
they will not do so for the same reason that humans found it difficult to m=
ove from pictographs to more complex forms of writing. The path forward was=
 not obvious.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2=
026/03/hieroglyphics.png=0A=0AFigure 13: Pictures are the most obvious path=
 to writing. Here is a collection of Egyptian pictographs that are easily d=
ecoded by a modern observer. (Fun fact: these symbols are available as Unic=
ode characters ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_Hieroglyphs_(Unicod=
e_block) ) .) Note that I use the word =E2=80=98pictograph=E2=80=99 to refe=
r to the literal meaning of each symbol. Egyptian =E2=80=98hieroglyphs=
=E2=80=99 are more complicated because they use the rebus principle to atta=
ch linguistic sounds to symbols.=0A=0AFor early writers, the hurdle was to =
somehow use pictures to encode messages that went beyond one-word statement=
s like =E2=80=98bull=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98snake=E2=80=99. For example, how =
would you use pictures to write this sentence?=0A=0A> The farmer went to th=
e market, sold his bull for $1000, invested the money in a Trump memecoin, =
and then went bankrupt.=0A>=0A=0AGiven the immense temporal gap between sim=
ple picture drawing and formal writing, we can infer that ancient humans st=
ruggled greatly with this problem. But they eventually discovered a good so=
lution, which was to use pictures in a more abstract way. Instead of using =
pictures to represent real-world things, they used pictures to represent li=
nguistic sounds.=0A=0AThis method is called the =E2=80=98rebus principle=
=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebus#Rebus_principle ) , and it =
works as follows. To encode a message that has no simple associated image, =
we first decompose the message into sounds. Then we map these sounds onto a=
 set of simple images. For example, if we combine the image of a bee and a =
leaf (as shown in Figure=C2=A014 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026=
/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-languag=
e-teaching/#fig-belief ) ), we can use the rebus principle to encode the En=
glish word =E2=80=98belief=E2=80=99. Clever!=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthet=
opdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/belief.png=0A=0AFigure 14: The rebus =
principle =E2=80=94 using symbols to encode linguistic sounds. Linguists be=
lieve that the use of the rebus principle is a crucial step for the develop=
ment of writing. With the rebus principle, one interprets images in terms o=
f the linguistic sounds they represent (rather than the literal objects bei=
ng displayed). In English, the symbols of a bee and a leaf can combine to r=
epresent the word =E2=80=98belief=E2=80=99.=0A=0ANow, to the modern (litera=
te) observer, the rebus principle seems both intuitive and obvious. After a=
ll, it=E2=80=99s the principle that underpins how we read and write. (More =
on that in a moment.) And yet, for the first proto-writers, the rebus princ=
iple was unintuitive. Why?=0A=0AWell, the problem seems to be that for huma=
ns, speaking is so effortless that we have little knowledge of how we do it=
. Yes, we speak by making sounds =E2=80=A6 but it is the meaning of these s=
ounds that we say and hear. Indeed, we have almost no conscious knowledge o=
f the sounds themselves. Or put another way, our brains naturally clump mea=
ning into spoken units called =E2=80=98words=E2=80=99. But our brains find =
it quite foreign to consciously decompose these words into meaningless soun=
ds. Yet the task for the first writers was to do just that =E2=80=94 to rev=
erse engineer what our brains do subconsciously. By all accounts, early wri=
ters found this task difficult. And to this day, children struggle to read =
largely because they struggle to decompose the sounds within words.=0A=0AAt=
 any rate, once the rebus principle was discovered, it allowed writing syst=
ems to evolve in two different ways. First, the symbols themselves tended t=
o become more abstract with time. The effect of this abstraction was to sim=
plify the act of writing, but to make learning how to read more difficult.=
=0A=0ASecond, the rebus principle allowed writers to explore the phonetic l=
evel at which to encode their language. Here, we might think that alphabeti=
c writing would be the most obvious path forward. But it was not. The alpha=
betic system was the least obvious approach to writing.=0A=0ATo the oral sp=
eaker, the natural unit of meaning is the individual word. Hence the most o=
bvious way of writing was to equate symbols with whole words. This =
=E2=80=98logographic=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logogram )  s=
ystem works perfectly well, and is the basis for Chinese writing.=0A=0AThe =
next step down the sound ladder is to use symbols to encode individual syll=
ables. This =E2=80=98syllabic=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syll=
abary )  approach is the basis for Japanese writing.=0A=0AFinally, the lowe=
st step down the sound ladder is to use symbols (an alphabet) to encode ind=
ividual =E2=80=98phonemes=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoneme =
) , which are the smallest unit of linguistic sound. The advantage of this =
=E2=80=98alphabetic=E2=80=99 approach is that it is by far the most efficie=
nt encoding method, requiring the user to memorize the least number of symb=
ols. 2 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-gettin=
g-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn2 )  However=
, the disadvantage, as Mark Liberman observes ( https://www.ling.upenn.edu/=
courses/Fall_2003/ling001/reading_writing.html ) , is that alphabetic writi=
ng places a =E2=80=9Cspecial burden=E2=80=9D on the reader, since it requir=
es that they gain conscious access to the lowest unit of linguistic sound =
=E2=80=94 a unit that is =E2=80=9Crelatively inaccessible to introspective =
scrutiny=E2=80=9D.=0A=0AIt is likely because of this =E2=80=9Cspecial burde=
n=E2=80=9D that whereas logographic and syllabic forms of writing evolved m=
ultiple times in different places, alphabetic writing seems to have evolved=
 only once ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_alphabet ) . It a=
rose out of the Semitic tradition ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Sin=
aitic_script ) , which developed a consonant-only system of writing. When t=
he ancient Greeks later borrowed these symbols, they adapted some of the le=
tters to notate vowels. All modern alphabets seem to have sprung from this =
singular lineage.=0A=0AThe point is that when children struggle to read alp=
habetic writing, they are in good company. Alphabetic writing is the least =
obvious way to store linguistic meaning. And it is also the writing method =
that is most susceptible to corruption.=0A=0AFor example, in modern English=
, there are nine different ways to encode the long =E2=80=98a=E2=80=99 soun=
d (as in halo, aid, ate, say, they, rein, great, eight, and straight). Who =
invented this absurd system? No one did. These different notations evolved =
from older phonetic principles that have since been corrupted, as pronuncia=
tion changed but spelling did not. Thus, English is littered with silent le=
tters that were once pronounced (as in =E2=80=98knight=E2=80=99), homonyms =
that once had distinct pronunciations (as in =E2=80=98meat=E2=80=99 and =
=E2=80=9Cmeet=E2=80=9D), and a myriad of ways to spell the same sound.3 ( h=
ttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at=
-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn3 )=0A=0ANo one would =
design such a convoluted system by choice. And yet, it is the system that E=
nglish children must learn. We fool ourselves if we think it is easy or =
=E2=80=98natural=E2=80=99.4 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/2=
8/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-tea=
ching/#fn4 )  And we doubly fool ourselves if we think that children can de=
duce the principles behind English phonetic encoding without explicit instr=
uction.=0A=0AHiding the decryption key=0A=0ATo summarize our foray into the=
 history of writing, reading is difficult to learn because it requires deve=
loping a set of low-level skills that are not intuitive or natural to the o=
ral speaker.=0A=0ANow, the tyranny is that for a good reader, these low-lev=
el skills have become so automatic that they are subconscious. Hence, a goo=
d reader might think it reasonable to teach a child to read without giving =
explicit instruction on the principles involved. This form of teaching is a=
 strikingly bad idea; and yet it is the method that dominates anglophone sc=
hooling.=0A=0AMore on that in a moment. But first, let me convince you (a g=
ood reader) that you have a set of low-level decoding skills that are large=
ly subconscious. Go ahead and read the following words aloud:=0A=0AAs you r=
ead, you no doubt realized that these are not English words. They are pseud=
owords that are assembled using the principles of English phonetics. (You c=
an generate more pseudowords here ( https://randomwordgenerator.com/fake-wo=
rd.php ) .)=0A=0AThe purpose of these pseudowords is to illustrate that goo=
d readers have internalized the low-level principles behind English phoneti=
c encoding. Good readers understand how letters combine to represent sounds=
, and how these sounds can be combined into words (real or not). Of course,=
 the corollary is that bad readers lack these low-level skills. Which is wh=
y, when faced with pseudowords, bad readers fall flat on their face.=0A=0AW=
ith this failure in mind, here is the trick to bad reading instruction: ask=
 students to read without teaching them the decryption key.=0A=0Ahttps://ec=
onomicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/divider.png=0A=0ATo de=
scribe a lesson in bad reading instruction, it seems only fair to use mysel=
f as an example. When my daughter started school, she was enrolled in Frenc=
h immersion, which meant that she=E2=80=99d learn to read French at school =
and English at home. Her home-school teacher would be me =E2=80=A6 Blair Fi=
x, PhD & VGR (very good reader).=0A=0ANow, at the time, I=E2=80=99d bought =
into the whole-language approach to reading instruction.5 ( https://economi=
csfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-c=
ase-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn5 )  Forget phonics, I thought. We=
=E2=80=99ll just start reading together, and my daughter will naturally pic=
k things up. But she didn=E2=80=99t. So with the benefit of hindsight, let =
me illustrate how things went wrong.=0A=0AOur first step was to read simple=
 picture books like the one shown in Figure=C2=A015 ( https://economicsfrom=
thetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-ag=
ainst-whole-language-teaching/#fig-apple ) . These books are called =
=E2=80=98levelled readers=E2=80=99, and they=E2=80=99re meant to be co-read=
, with prompts from the pictures. First, I=E2=80=99d read the book. Then my=
 daughter would =E2=80=98read=E2=80=99 it back to me. Things seemed to be g=
oing well =E2=80=A6 or so I thought.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.c=
om/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/apples_red_crop.png=0A=0AFigure 15: Teaching =
children how to avoid reading. This is an excerpt from the book First Littl=
e Readers =E2=80=93 What Is Red? ( https://archive.org/details/firstlittler=
eaderswhatisred )  It is typical of the levelled-reader format. Note the re=
petitive sentence structure, which can be easily memorized and recited base=
d on cues from the pictures. Note also the difficulty of the actual decodin=
g task. In this supposed =E2=80=98Level A=E2=80=99 reader, kids are asked t=
o decode the words =E2=80=98apples=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98strawberries=
=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 words that are phonetically complicated. In short, this=
 book practically begs children to not read the text, and to instead recite=
 the message from pictographic cues.=0A=0AWhat I realize now is that these =
levelled readers actually teach children how to avoid reading. Again, the h=
istory of writing is instructive as to why. To develop alphabet writing, pe=
ople had to realize that linguistic meaning (i.e.=C2=A0words) could be brok=
en down into sounds, and that these sounds could be encoded into symbols:=
=0A=0ALearning to read therefore involves the reverse operation. The learne=
r must take symbols, map them onto sounds, and decode the meaning:=0A=0ALoo=
king at levelled readers, these books make no attempt to teach the reading =
decryption algorithm. Instead, they take a repetitive sentence structure an=
d map it onto a set of richly illustrated images. Of course, kids love this=
 format, because it provides a far more obvious path for encoding meaning. =
Indeed, it is the same path taken by the first writers, who took meaning an=
d mapped it onto pictures:=0A=0AWhen we ask a child to =E2=80=98read=
=E2=80=99 an illustrated (levelled) reader, they naturally take the easiest=
 path by decoding the message from the picture:=0A=0ANow, the problem here =
is that asking a child to decode meaning from pictures actively misleads th=
em about how reading actually works. Historically, the path from pictograph=
s to alphabetic writing was long and torturous. Indeed, the path was so dif=
ficult that it happened only once. Hence, it is completely unreasonable to =
request that a child use pictographs as a tool for deducing alphabetic prin=
ciples. Many children will not make this conceptual leap.=0A=0AInstead, whe=
n children are shown pictographs with associated text, what tends to happen=
 is that they memorize a few of the simpler looking words, and then they re=
cite (or simply guess) the rest of the words from the context (which includ=
es the picture and the repetitive sentence structure). Unsurprisingly, rese=
archers have observed this guessing behavior countless times. The strategy =
occurs because actually reading the words on the page is the hardest and le=
ast intuitive option for decoding meaning. Guessing the message from the pi=
ctures and the context is far easier. And so that=E2=80=99s what kids do.=
=0A=0AWith word guessing in mind, here is where things get weird. When whol=
e-language theorists observed children=E2=80=99s guessing tactic, they inte=
rpreted it as a learning strategy. Indeed, they enshrined it in a pedagogic=
al approach called the =E2=80=98cueing method=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Three_cueing ) , in which children are taught to read text by l=
ooking first to the picture, next to the syntactic context, and last to the=
 actual word.=0A=0AIn short, the whole-language method took a reading avoid=
ance tactic (guessing words from context) and transformed it into a =
=E2=80=98strategy=E2=80=99 for learning how to read. As you might guess, th=
e effect of this strategy is to leave the worst readers behind.=0A=0ATeachi=
ng the decryption key=0A=0AThe irony of whole-language pedagogy is that whe=
n it swept through anglophone schools in the 1980s and 1990s, cognitive sci=
entists were codifying ( https://eric.ed.gov/?id=3DED430366 )  the best pra=
ctices in reading instruction. Suffice it to say that these best practices =
are not what whole-language theory preaches.=0A=0AIn a nutshell, cognitive =
scientists discovered that kids struggle to read for the same reason that h=
umans struggled to develop writing. For the oral speaker, it is unnatural t=
o decompose words into sounds. Hence, kids who struggle to read typically l=
ack =E2=80=98phonemic awareness=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 they do not hear the sou=
nds within words. And so the solution is to teach this skill. Teach kids th=
at English words are built from a repertoire of several dozen sounds ( http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_phonology ) . Teach kids how to segment w=
ords into sounds. Teach kids how sounds map onto the alphabet. Yes, this in=
struction is low-level work. But for young children, it is exciting new kno=
wledge. They love it!=0A=0AOnce kids grasp the basics of how the alphabet r=
epresents sounds, they=E2=80=99re ready to read three-letter words like =
=E2=80=98sit=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98hat=E2=80=99. Next, they can read these =
words in simple sentences. Crucially, the practice reading must lack pictur=
e cues, because pictures provide a way to avoid the cognitively demanding t=
ask of decoding words. (Figure=C2=A016 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.co=
m/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-l=
anguage-teaching/#fig-thr )  shows a sample reading task from Treasure Hunt=
 Reading ( https://treasurehunt.prenda.co/helpful-adults ) , a free structu=
red literacy program.)=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/=
uploads/2026/03/thr.png=0A=0AFigure 16: A typical reading task in a structu=
red literacy program. In this example from Treasure Hunt Reading ( https://=
treasurehunt.prenda.co/helpful-adults ) , kids are asked to form and read s=
imple three letter words with a repeating phonic pattern. Notice that this =
task comes on page 40 of the workbook, after the required consonant and vow=
el sounds have been taught.=0A=0AFinally, reading ability can be built iter=
atively by adding new sounds and new ways to encode each sound. (Remember, =
English is a phonetic mess.) At each step, kids read text that obeys only t=
he phonetic principles that they=E2=80=99ve been taught. And because kids h=
ave been taught the skills for success, something surprising happens. They =
learn to read!=0A=0AThis evidence-backed approach to reading instruction is=
 called =E2=80=98structured literacy=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Structured_literacy ) , and it should be standard practice in every elem=
entary school. But it is not. Instead, the dominant approach (at least unti=
l recently) has been to shower kids in text and hope that they deduce the k=
ey for decryption. Many kids fail to make this deduction, and they grow up =
to be life-long dysfunctional readers.=0A=0APart III: The case against whol=
e-language instruction=0A=0ANow that we understand why reading is hard to l=
earn, I want to build the case against whole-language pedagogy. I=E2=80=
=99m going to argue that whole-language teaching is the main wedge that=
=E2=80=99s widening the gap between the best and worst high-school readers.=
=0A=0AMy case rests on seven lines of evidence, listed below. At root, my a=
rgument is simple. If we do not teach kids the code for decrypting English =
words, it is the worst readers who suffer, with effects that last a lifetim=
e.=0A=0AThe case against whole-language instruction=0A=0A* Whole-language m=
ethods are ubiquitous=0A* Whole-language instruction harms struggling reade=
rs=0A* If whole-language instruction is to blame, the timing checks out=0A*=
 Early reading ability determines later success=0A* A decoding deficit crea=
tes a compound reading failure=0A* A decoding deficit is a lifelong problem=
=0A* The widening reading-score gap is reversible=0A=0A1. Whole-language me=
thods are ubiquitous=0A=0AThe first piece of evidence implicating whole-lan=
guage methods in the widening reading-score gap is the fact that these meth=
ods are ubiquitous. For example, a 2019 survey ( https://www.edweek.org/res=
earch-center/research-center-reports/early-reading-instruction-results-of-a=
-national-survey )  found that 75% of US K-2 teachers taught the =E2=80=
=98three cueing=E2=80=99 method for deducing words from their context =
=E2=80=94 a method that mistakenly reinforces the evasion tactic that strug=
gling readers use to avoid decoding words.6 ( https://economicsfromthetopdo=
wn.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-wh=
ole-language-teaching/#fn6 ) :=0A=0ANow, the good news is that in the last =
few years, the cueing method has grown increasingly unpopular, and has even=
 been banned in 15 US states ( https://www.apmreports.org/story/2025/10/16/=
legislators-reading-laws-sold-a-story ) . But the bad news is that for toda=
y=E2=80=99s high-school students, the damage has already been done.=0A=0A2.=
 Whole-language instruction harms struggling readers=0A=0AThe second piece =
of evidence implicating whole-language instruction in the widening reading-=
score gap is the fact that this method harms struggling readers.=0A=0AThat =
was the conclusion drawn from a large study ( https://www.cresp.udel.edu/re=
search-project/efficacy-follow-study-long-term-effects-reading-recovery-i3-=
scale/ )  of the =E2=80=98Reading Recovery=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Reading_Recovery )  program, which is a whole-language interventio=
n designed to bring below-grade-level readers up to speed. In this study, a=
 large group of struggling first-grade readers received intensive one-on-on=
e instruction from a Reading Recovery expert. The students=E2=80=99 progres=
s was then tracked over time and compared to a group of struggling readers =
who did not receive an intervention.=0A=0AIn 2017, the researchers reported=
 ( https://www.cresp.udel.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Evidence-for-Early=
-Literacy-Intervention_-The-Impacts-of-Reading.pdf )  that the initial inte=
rvention was a success: by the end of their tutoring, the Reading Recovery =
students were doing substantially better than their peers. Then came the co=
ld water. When the researchers returned to track student progress a few yea=
rs later, they found ( https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/19345747=
.2023.2209092 )  a strikingly different pattern. By third and fourth grade,=
 the students who=E2=80=99d participated in the Reading Recovery program we=
re not ahead of their peers =E2=80=A6 they were between a half to a full gr=
ade level behind.=0A=0AAlthough the researchers struggled to explain this n=
egative effect, the problem seems obvious in hindsight. Whole-language meth=
ods promote the wrote memorization of words, which is an effective strategy=
 when the vocabulary is small. But as the reading material gets more comple=
x, memorization methods fail, and the students=E2=80=99 decoding deficit re=
ars its head. And because whole-language instruction actively dissuades stu=
dents from learning how to decode words, their decoding deficit grows worse=
 with time.=0A=0A3. If whole-language instruction is to blame, the timing c=
hecks out=0A=0AThe third piece of evidence implicating whole-language instr=
uction in the widening reading-score gap is the fact that the timing checks=
 out. It was in the mid-1980s when whole-language instruction began to spre=
ad. And it was in the mid-1990s when high-school reading scores began to dr=
op. If we add a decade delay to allow the first whole-language recipients t=
o advance through school, we=E2=80=99d expect to see the high-school effect=
s of this method appear during the mid-1990s =E2=80=A6 just when high-schoo=
l reading scores began to drop.=0A=0AOf course, we don=E2=80=99t have rigor=
ous data that tracks the spread of whole-language methods. But we can get a=
 rough sense for the popularity of this approach by tracking the frequency =
of the phrase =E2=80=98whole language=E2=80=99 within English books. When w=
e do so, we find that the phrase became popular in the 1980s. The top panel=
