s-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fi=
g-whole-language )  shows the pattern. If we suppose that this word frequen=
cy indicates the popularity of whole-language instruction during the early =
years of schooling, we=E2=80=99d expect to see the high-school effects of t=
hese methods appear about a decade later, during the mid-1990s (dashed curv=
e).=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/who=
le_lang.png=0A=0AFigure 17: The whole-language impulse. The top panel shows=
 the frequency of the phrase =E2=80=98whole language=E2=80=99 in the Google=
 English corpus (a large sample of English books). The dashed-red line show=
s this frequency with a ten year delay, used to indicate the potential high=
-school effects of whole-language education on those who endured it during =
