 18: Third-grade reading ability strongly determines success during high sc=
hool and beyond. In the mid-1990s, Chapin Hall researchers ( https://www.ch=
apinhall.org/research/third-grade-reading-level-predictive-of-later-life-ou=
tcomes/ )  measured the reading ability of a cohort of third-grade students=
 in the Chicago Public Schools system. Then they tracked student progress o=
ver time. The researchers found that high-school graduation rates and colle=
ge attendance were both strongly determined by reading ability in grade thr=
ee, as shown here. [Sources and methods ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.c=
om/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-=
language-teaching/#sources-and-methods ) ]=0A=0A5. A decoding deficit creat=
es a compound reading failure=0A=0AThe fifth piece of evidence implicating =
whole-language methods in the widening reading-score gap is the fact that b=
y downplaying decoding skills (and encouraging students to guess at words),=
 the approach likely creates a compound reading failure.=0A=0ATo understand=
 this effect, realize that reading comprehension is the product of two dist=
inct skills. Reading comprehension depends firstly on the ability to decode=
 words. And it depends secondly on oral comprehension. According to the =
=E2=80=98simple view of reading=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Si=
mple_view_of_reading ) , reading comprehension is the product of these two =
abilities:=0A=0ANow in principle, decoding skill is separate from oral comp=
rehension, which is why someone can be fluent but illiterate. That said, in=
 literate cultures, oral comprehension tends to be a function of decoding a=
bility itself. And that=E2=80=99s because writing is the most potent source=
 of knowledge.=0A=0ASimply by reading, a good decoder can learn about new w=
ords and new ideas, causing their oral comprehension to grow with time. In =
contrast, a poor decoder struggles to unlock the knowledge contained within=
 books, which means that their oral comprehension remains stunted. But here=
 is the kicker. Because reading comprehension depends on the product of dec=
oding and oral abilities, poor decoders suffer a compound failure. Their po=
or decoding hinders their oral comprehension, and so their reading comprehe=
nsion suffers doubly.=0A=0AFigure=C2=A019 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown=
.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whol=
e-language-teaching/#fig-duff )  shows an example of this compound failure.=
 The data comes from a longitudinal study ( https://www.researchgate.net/pu=
blication/274094131_The_Influence_of_Reading_on_Vocabulary_Growth_A_Case_fo=
r_a_Matthew_Effect )  of 485 students in Iowa and Illinois, whose school pr=
ogress was tracked throughout 1990s. The chart illustrates how students=
=E2=80=99 vocabulary depended on their decoding skills, which were measured=
 in grade 4. (Vocabulary is a crude proxy for oral comprehension.) Over tim=
e, students=E2=80=99 vocabularies tended to increase, but not at the same r=
ate. Instead, the best fourth-grade decoders had the greatest vocabulary gr=
owth, while the worst fourth-grad decoders had the least vocabulary growth.=
=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/duff.p=
ng=0A=0AFigure 19: Poor decoding skills lead to a stunted vocabulary. In th=
e 1990s, Dawna Duff and colleagues ( https://www.researchgate.net/publicati=
on/274094131_The_Influence_of_Reading_on_Vocabulary_Growth_A_Case_for_a_Mat=
thew_Effect )  tracked vocabulary growth among a cohort of American student=
s. This chart shows how vocabularies grew as a function of decoding ability=
, measured in fourth grade. While all students saw their vocabularies incre=
ase with time, the poor decoders saw the least growth. Assuming that these =
poor decoders retained their decoding deficit throughout school, by high sc=
hool they would suffer from a compound reading failure, with worse decoding=
 skills and a smaller vocabulary. [Sources and methods ( https://economicsf=
romthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case=
-against-whole-language-teaching/#sources-and-methods ) ]=0A=0AIf the poor =
fourth-grade decoders retained their decoding deficit as they aged (a reaso=
nable assumption), we can surmise that by high-school, they suffered from a=
 compound failure: both their decoding and their oral comprehension lagged =
behind their peers, leading to significantly worse reading comprehension. I=
n short, to the extent that whole-language instruction hinders the developm=
ent of decoding skills, we expect that by adulthood, it creates a compound =
failure of reading comprehension.=0A=0A6. A decoding deficit is a lifelong =
problem=0A=0AThe sixth piece of evidence implicating whole-language methods=
 in the widening reading-score gap is the fact that decoding deficits are n=
ot solely a childhood problem. They typically remain present well into adul=
thood.=0A=0ATrue, poor decoders often develop coping skills for parsing tex=
t =E2=80=94 skills like memorizing sight words and guessing unfamiliar word=
s from their context. Unfortunately, these coping strategies do not solve t=
he core decoding deficit, which remains visible to anyone who cares to look=
.=0A=0AThe way to unearth a decoding deficiency is ask people to read pseud=
owords =E2=80=94 fake words that are constructed from real English phonetic=
s. When tasked with parsing such words, poor readers reveal their core defi=
cit: they have not mastered the principles of English phonetics.=0A=0AFigur=
e=C2=A020 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-get=
ting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-decodin=
g )  shows a striking example of this deficit. The data comes from research=
 conducted by Molly Minus ( https://eric.ed.gov/?id=3DED352641 )  during th=
e 1990s. As part of her PhD research, Minus measured decoding ability among=
 three groups of adults:=0A=0A* Upper-level university students=0A* College=
 students taking remedial reading courses=0A* Prisoners receiving reading i=
nstruction=0A=0AMinus found stark differences between these groups. When ta=
sked with reading 50 pseudowords, the university students got almost all of=
 them correct (top panel). The college students faired worse (middle panel)=
. And the prisoners? Well, they were abysmal, getting an average of 8 words=
 correct (bottom panel).=0A=0AThe point here is that well into adulthood, t=
he main driver of functional illiteracy is the inability to decode words =
=E2=80=94 an inability that whole-language teaching actively promotes.=0A=
=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/decoding.=
png=0A=0AFigure 20: Decoding ability among three groups of adults. In the e=
arly 1990s, Molly Minus measured decoding skills ( https://eric.ed.gov/?id=
=3DED352641 )  among three groups of adults: upper level university student=
s (top panel), college students in remedial reading courses (middle panel),=
 and prisoners receiving reading instruction (bottom panel). This chart sho=
ws the distribution of decoding scores within each group. (The task was to =
read fifty pseudowords.) Minus found that decoding skill varied predictably=
 by group. The university students were excellent decoders, while the priso=
ner were horrible. [Sources and methods ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.c=
om/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-=
language-teaching/#sources-and-methods ) ]=0A=0A7. The widening reading-sco=
re gap is reversible=0A=0ANow to what is perhaps the key piece of evidence =
implicating whole-language teaching in the widening reading-score gap. It s=
eems that this growing gap is not inevitable, and that it can be reversed b=
y dumping whole-language methods and replacing them with structured literac=
y. Interestingly, we can thank the state of Mississippi for demonstrating t=
his fact.=0A=0APerpetually the poorest US state, Mississippi once produced =
some of the nation=E2=80=99s worst readers. As recently as 2013, Mississipp=
i=E2=80=99s fourth-grade reading scores were in last place. Yet by 2024, it=
 had turned things around and was among the top ten states. Figure=C2=A021 =
( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse=
-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-miss-rank )  show=
s the transformation.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/u=
ploads/2026/03/miss_rank.png=0A=0AFigure 21: The Mississippi miracle. This =
chart shows Mississippi=E2=80=99s state rank in fourth-grade reading scores=
. (Note the reverse scale on the vertical axis.) For decades, Mississippi s=
at at the bottom of the reading-score heap. But after 2013, it clawed its w=
ay into the top ten =E2=80=94 a remarkable transformation that=E2=80=99s of=
ten dubbed the =E2=80=98Mississippi miracle=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mississippi_Miracle ) . [Sources and methods ( https://economicsf=
romthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case=
-against-whole-language-teaching/#sources-and-methods ) ]=0A=0ASo what happ=
ened? Did Mississippi suddenly get rich? Did its children stop watching TV?=
 No and no. What happened is that in 2013, Mississippi overhauled how it ta=
ught kids to read.=0A=0ATo make sense of this overhaul, realize that in the=
 1990s, Mississippi followed other states in embracing the whole-language a=
pproach to reading. Curriculum documents from the time illustrate the educa=
tional dogma. In 1996, Mississippi=E2=80=99s Department of Education declar=
ed ( https://archive.org/details/ERIC_ED430248 )  that among first-grade st=
udents, =E2=80=9C[r]eading and writing are no longer viewed as isolated tas=
ks to be taught and tested=E2=80=9D. Then, as if to foreshadow what would f=
ollow, the document argues for a =E2=80=9Charmony=E2=80=9D of strategies as=
 students =E2=80=9Cattempt to understand how reading and writing work=
=E2=80=9D (my emphasis).=0A=0AIt=E2=80=99s with this possibility for failur=
e that we should interpret the patterns in Figure=C2=A022 ( https://economi=
csfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-c=
ase-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-miss-diff ) . In the top panel, I=
=E2=80=99ve plotted the change in Mississippian fourth-grade reading scores=
 between 1992 and 1994 (measured as a function of reading-score percentile)=
. Notice the Z-shaped trend: over this period, a widening gap emerged betwe=
en the best and worst readers. Well that=E2=80=99s curious. That=E2=80=
=99s the same type of gap that emerged among US high-school students over t=
he last three decades. (See Figure=C2=A03 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown=
.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whol=
e-language-teaching/#fig-percentile-diff ) .). Perhaps Mississippi=E2=80=
=99s embrace of whole-language methods is telling us something.=0A=0Ahttps:=
//economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/miss_diff.png=0A=
=0AFigure 22: Mississippi=E2=80=99s widening and then narrowing reading-sco=
re gap. This chart shows the change in Mississippian fourth-grade reading s=
cores as a function of reading-score percentile, captured during two differ=
ent eras. The top panel shows the reading-score change between 1992 and 199=
4, an era when the state was rapidly adopting whole-language methods. Over =
this period, a widening reading-score gap emerged, with the best fourth-gra=
de readers getting better, and the worst readers getting worse. In contrast=
, the bottom panel shows the reading-score change between 2011 and 2019, an=
 era when the state abandoned whole-language methods and implemented a stru=
ctured-literacy approach to reading instruction. (I=E2=80=99ve halted the d=
ata in 2019 to avoid any pandemic-related artifacts.) Over this period, the=
 reading-score gap narrowed significantly. While all fourth-grade readers i=
mproved, the best readers improved the least, while the worst readers impro=
ved the most. [Sources and methods ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/20=
26/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-langu=
age-teaching/#sources-and-methods ) ]=0A=0ANow let=E2=80=99s look at the bo=
ttom panel in Figure=C2=A022 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/=
28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-te=
aching/#fig-miss-diff ) , which plots the change in Mississippian fourth-gr=
ade reading scores from 2011 to 2019. Notice that the pattern looks starkly=
 different than the one above. During the 2010s, all fourth-grade Mississip=
pian readers improved. However, the worst readers improved the most, while =
the best readers improved the least.=0A=0AWhat caused this reverse effect? =
Fortunately, we know exactly what happened. In 2013, Carey Wright ( https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carey_Wright )  became Mississippi=E2=80=99s state S=
uperintendent of Education. A proponent of evidence-based instruction, Wrig=
ht oversaw a massive change in how Mississippi taught reading. Whole-langua=
ge methods were abandoned and replaced with a focus on systematic phonics a=
nd phonemic instruction. The new approach included extensive support for te=
achers, funding for the early detection of reading problems, and (most cont=
roversially) a =E2=80=98third-grade gate=E2=80=99, which required that all =
third-grade students pass a mandatory reading test before proceeding to the=
 next grade.7 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are=
-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn7 )=
=0A=0AThe results of this teaching experiment were nothing short of dramati=
c. Mississippi=E2=80=99s fourth-grade reading scores were vaulted from wors=
t in class to among the top ten. But more interesting, in my view, is the s=
tructure of this =E2=80=98Mississippi miracle=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Mississippi_Miracle )  =E2=80=94 the fact that it targeted the =
worst readers and helped them the most. Mississippi=E2=80=99s experiment st=
rongly suggests that the widening skill gap between the best and worst high=
-school readers is not inevitable, and that it=E2=80=99s been driven by who=
le-language pedagogy =E2=80=94 a teaching approach that systematically fail=
s the worst readers.=0A=0AWhen the method creates the disease=0A=0AWhen par=
ents send their kids to school, they no doubt assume that the teacher uses =
the best methods for instruction, much as a patient assumes that their doct=
or uses the best forms of medicine. Unfortunately, if the history of scienc=
e tells us anything, it is that best practices are not guaranteed.=0A=0AThe=
 problem is that once a flawed practice becomes institutionalized, it is di=
fficult for the practitioner to discern that their method is unsound. If yo=
u practice only what your mentor preached (and you=E2=80=99re surrounded by=
 others who do the same), the failure of your method becomes invisible. Whi=
ch is why doctors practiced bloodletting for centuries, yet were oblivious =
to the fact that it tended to kill their patients.=0A=0AIt=E2=80=99s within=
 this context that we should interpret the whole-language movement. It prom=
oted a flawed teaching method that, once institutionalized, became invisibl=
e to its practitioners. When children did learn to read (despite their poor=
 instruction), it was proof that the method worked. And if the child failed=
, they were just =E2=80=98slow learners=E2=80=99 who=E2=80=99d eventually g=
et the gist of reading. In short, it was the method that succeeded, but the=
 individual child who failed.=0A=0AStill, there=E2=80=99s the question of h=
ow such a flawed practice managed to become a tradition. Did whole-language=
 teaching become popular because it contained a kernel of truth? I think th=
e answer is no. The whole-language approach became popular because it told =
a story ( https://features.apmreports.org/sold-a-story/ )  that people want=
ed to hear. Whole-language theory sold the idea that learning to read is as=
 natural as learning to speak. The message, then, is that the teacher can e=
mpower their students largely by getting out of the way. So forget lectures=
. Forget drills. Forget explicit instruction. Just give kids a chance to ex=
plore great literature, and they will naturally learn how to read.=0A=0ATo =
grasp the appeal of this idea, we must understand the context in which it e=
merged. Prior to the 1960s, anglophone schooling was a dictatorial affair. =
It was a place where the teacher was a sergeant and the kids were compliant=
 enlistees. It was an environment that did not exactly stimulate high-minde=
d thinking. It was this dictatorial environment that whole-language propone=
nts rejected. They sold (and still sell ( https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/f=
ull/10.1111/eie.12096 ) ) their approach as a =E2=80=9Cdemocratic=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Chumanistic=E2=80=9D method that empowers =E2=80=9Cteachers=
 and students alike=E2=80=9D. In short, the spread of whole-language teachi=
ng had more to do with political ideals than with any evidence that the met=
hod was sound.8 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-a=
re-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn8 )=
=0A=0ANow, the irony is that although whole-language methods were billed as=
 a tool for empowering all children, what they actually did was to empower =
the best students =E2=80=94 the kids who learned to read effortlessly, and =
who benefited from have time (and resources) to practice their skills. But =
for the kids who struggled to decode words, the whole-language environment =
was downright confusing, since they were being asked to =E2=80=98practice=
=E2=80=99 a task that they found bewildering. It was the equivalent of givi=
ng a ten-year old integral calculus and saying =E2=80=9CDo the math, kid. I=
=E2=80=99m empowering you by not teaching you how it works.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AO=
f course, the failure of whole-language methods doesn=E2=80=99t mean that w=
rote dictatorial teaching is the way to go. It is not. The real message is =
that higher-level abilities do not come from the ether; they depend on the =
mastery of lower-level skills.=0A=0AGreat jazz musicians improvise effortle=
ssly because they=E2=80=99ve internalized low-level skills like scales and =
chord progressions. Great mathematicians produced abstract proofs because t=
hey=E2=80=99ve mastered the low-level skills behind arithmetic and algebra.=
 Great writers produce compelling literature because they=E2=80=99ve been t=
aught the low-level mechanics of their language. And good readers can parse=
 text accurately and rapidly because they grasp the low-level algorithm of =
how symbols encode linguistic sounds.=0A=0AIn each case, choosing to not te=
ach these low-level skills isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=98democratic=E2=80=99. It i=
sn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=98humanistic=E2=80=99. It is the definition of regressi=
ve. Choosing to not teach low-level skills is a recipe for selecting the le=
ast gifted students and systematically leaving them behind. It is a recipe =
for producing the outcomes we now observe =E2=80=A6 a widening gap between =
the best readers and the worst readers.=0A=0AOf course, the evidence agains=
t whole-language teaching does not get smartphones and algorithmic slop off=
 the hook for polluting our social environment. But then again, when kids s=
truggle to merely decode words, they have little reason to get off their ph=
ones and actually read.=0A=0ASupport this blog=0A=0AHi folks, Blair Fix her=
