antile function for reading scores=0A=0AThe most fine-grain data provided b=
y the NAEP consists of =E2=80=98distribution percentages=E2=80=99 =E2=80=
=94 the percentage of students with reading scores within a given ten-point=
 range. To work with this data, I smooth it using a spline function.=0A=0AF=
igure=C2=A023 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are=
-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-int=
erp-dist )  shows my approach. Here, the points show the empirical data fro=
m the NAEP. Each point is located at the midpoint of the reading-score bin,=
 and shows the percentage of students within each bin. To infer the smoothe=
d distribution behind this binned data, I interpolate between data points u=
sing a spline function (the curve in Figure=C2=A023 ( https://economicsfrom=
thetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-ag=
ainst-whole-language-teaching/#fig-interp-dist ) ). I then treat this curve=
 as a probability distribution for reading scores.=0A=0AFrom this estimated=
 probability distribution, I then infer the quantile function, which consis=
ts of reading scores as a function of reading-score percentile. Figure=
=C2=A024 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-gett=
ing-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-quantile=
 )  shows the inferred quantile function for all US grade 12 students in 20=
24. Once I=E2=80=99ve created the quantile functions for all of the desired=
 data (various years and various demographic groups), I use these functions=
 to estimate changes in percentile score over time.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsf=
romthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/interp_dist.png=0A=0AFigure 23=
: Distribution of US grade 12 reading scores in 2024. This chart illustrate=
s my method for smoothing the =E2=80=98distribution percentages=E2=80=99 da=
ta provided by the NAEP. The empirical data consists of binned values repor=
ting the portion of students with reading scores within a given ten-point r=
ange. Here, blue points show this empirical data, with the point placed at =
the midpoint of each reading-score bin. To estimate the complete distributi=
on beneath this binned data, I interpolate between points using a spline fu=
nction, as illustrated by the curve. I then treat this curve as probability=
 distribution for reading scores.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/=
wp-content/uploads/2026/03/quantile_function.png=0A=0AFigure 24: The inferr=
ed quantile function for US grade 12 reading scores in 2024. This chart sho=
ws inferred (smoothed) values for US grade 12 reading score as a function o=
f read-score percentile. To construct this quantile function, I use the est=
imated probability distribution from Figure=C2=A023 ( https://economicsfrom=
thetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-ag=
ainst-whole-language-teaching/#fig-interp-dist ) . I then use this smoothed=
 quantile function to estimate changes in percentile reading score over tim=
e. (These changes are not shown here.)=0A=0AWord frequency (Figure=C2=A017 =
( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse=
-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-whole-language ) =
)=0A=0AData for the frequency of =E2=80=98whole language=E2=80=99 and =
=E2=80=98balanced literacy=E2=80=99 is from the Google Ngrams dataset, down=
loaded with the R package ngramr.=0A=0AHigh-school graduation rates by thir=
d-grade reading ability (Figure=C2=A018 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.c=
om/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-=
language-teaching/#fig-grade-three ) )=0A=0AData comes from Figures 4 and 5=
 in the report =E2=80=98Third Grade Reading Level Predictive of Later Life =
Outcomes=E2=80=99 ( https://www.chapinhall.org/research/third-grade-reading=
-level-predictive-of-later-life-outcomes/ ) , by Lesnick, Goerge, and Smith=
gall. The study tracks a large cohort of Chicago Public Schools students as=
 they progress through school. (To work with this data, I digitized it usin=
g Engauge Digitizer.) Note that Lesnick and colleagues define reading grade=
 level as follows:=0A=0Abelow grade level: reading scores below the nationa=
l 25th percentile=0A=0Aat grade level: reading scores above the national 25=
th percentile and below the national 75th percentile=0A=0Aabove grade level=
: reading scores above the national 75th percentile=0A=0AVocabulary growth =
as a function of decoding skill (Figure=C2=A019 ( https://economicsfromthet=
opdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-agains=
t-whole-language-teaching/#fig-duff ) )=0A=0AData is from Figure 2 in the p=
aper =E2=80=98The Influence of Reading on Vocabulary Growth: A Case for a M=
atthew Effect=E2=80=99 ( https://www.researchgate.net/publication/274094131=
_The_Influence_of_Reading_on_Vocabulary_Growth_A_Case_for_a_Matthew_Effect =
)  by Duff, Tomblin, and Catts. The study tracked the progress of 485 child=
ren in Iowa and Illinois, beginning in 1993. Note that what I call =
=E2=80=98decoding ability=E2=80=99, Duff and colleagues call =E2=80=98readi=
ng ability=E2=80=99. But what they actually measure is the fourth-grade abi=
lity to decode pseudowords and selected sight words. (To work with this dat=
a, I digitized it using Engauge Digitizer.)=0A=0AAdult decoding ability (Fi=
gure=C2=A020 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-=
getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-deco=
ding ) )=0A=0AData is from Figures 6, 7, and 8 in Molly Minus=E2=80=99 pape=
r =E2=80=98The Relationship of Phonemic Awareness to Reading Level and the =
Effects of Phonemic Awareness Instruction on the Decoding Skills of Adult D=
isabled Readers=E2=80=99 ( https://eric.ed.gov/?id=3DED352641 ) . (I digiti=
zed the data with Engauge Digitizer.)=0A=0ANote that Minus also measured =
=E2=80=98phonemic awareness=E2=80=99 in her three sample groups. (Phonemic =
awareness is the ability to identify the sounds within words.) As with deco=
ding ability, she found that phonemic awareness varied starkly between grou=
ps, as shown in Figure=C2=A025 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/0=
3/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-=
teaching/#fig-phonemic ) . This evidence reinforces the standard scientific=
 picture of reading. Good readers can parse the sounds within words. Bad re=
aders cannot.=0A=0Ahttps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2=
026/03/phonemic.png=0A=0AFigure 25: Phonemic awareness among three groups o=
f adults. This chart shows Molly Minus=E2=80=99s measurements of phonemic a=
wareness (the ability to decompose the sounds within words) in three sample=
s of adults. Data is from her Figures 10, 11, and 12 in Minus (1992) ( http=
s://www.proquest.com/openview/3896155685d77b4f55d0e99f07a1b689/1 ) . Note t=
he large disparity between prisoners and university students.=0A=0ANotes=0A=
=0AI=E2=80=99ve used the word =E2=80=98pictograph=E2=80=99 to refer to Egyp=
tian symbols that are meant to be interpreted literally. In contrast, Egypt=
ian =E2=80=98hieroglyphs=E2=80=99 use the rebus principle to encode more co=
mplex forms of thought.=0A=0AIntriguingly, Egyptian hieroglyphs illustrate =
a key downside of the rebus principle, which is that the symbols can only b=
e deciphered if the reader has knowledge of the spoken language being encod=
ed. For example, to the French speaker, the image of a bee and a leaf (Figu=
re=C2=A014 ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-ge=
tting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fig-belief=
 ) ) would not elicit the concept of =E2=80=98belief=E2=80=99 (=E2=80=98cro=
yance=E2=80=99 in French). It is because of this oral dependence that the E=
gyptian hieroglyphs spent thousands of years as unintelligible nonsense. Wh=
en the ancient Egyptian dialect died out, no one had a clue what the surviv=
ing symbols meant. The key to decoding these messages came only in 1799, wi=
th the discovery of the Rosetta stone ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roset=
ta_Stone )  =E2=80=94 a tablet that contained identical messages encoded in=
 Greek, hieroglyphic Egyptian, and demotic Egyptian.=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( ht=
tps://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-=
reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fnref1 )=0A=0AWestern sch=
olars have long argued that the alphabet is the most efficient way to encod=
e language, since it requires memorizing the least number of symbols. (Some=
 scholars have gone so far as to claim that the alphabet was essential for =
rationality ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alphabet_effect ) .) Of course,=
 arguments about the superiority of alphabetic writing are no doubt driven =
in part by ethnocentrism. But in light of the way we now use computers, I t=
hink the =E2=80=98efficiency=E2=80=99 argument is probably correct.=0A=0ATo=
 enter non-alphabetic characters on a computer, the solution is invariably =
to use the Latin alphabet, at least in part, to phonetically type the desir=
ed non-alphabetic symbol. (See, for example, the pinyin system ( https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinyin )  for typing Chinese symbols.) Hence, it seems =
unlikely that we could have modern computers without the alphabet.=E2=86=
=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-=
getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fnref2 )=
=0A=0AMuch of the phonetic corruption in modern English results from an eve=
nt called the =E2=80=98Great Vowel Shift=E2=80=99 ( https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Great_Vowel_Shift ) . During this shift, which began in the 1400s, v=
owel sounds that were previously distinct slowly evolved into the same soun=
d. Since the spelling of these sounds didn=E2=80=99t change, the rules of E=
nglish phonetics became more confusing. Similar complications happen when l=
anguages merge. The new hybrid is left with phonetic principles from both p=
arent tongues. English is itself a mutt of a language ( https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Foreign-language_influences_in_English )  =E2=80=94 part Germani=
c, part Latin, and part French.=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromth=
etopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-agai=
nst-whole-language-teaching/#fnref3 )=0A=0AIn a fascinating 2021 paper ( ht=
tps://aclanthology.org/2021.sigtyp-1.1/ ) , Xavier Marjou used a neural net=
work to estimate how difficult various languages are to read and write. He =
fed the neural network fixed-length samples of various languages, and then =
asked it predict pronunciation from spelling (i.e.=C2=A0read) and predict s=
pelling from pronunciation (i.e.=C2=A0write). In his test, English performe=
d horribly. The bot had a write accuracy of 36% and read accuracy of just 3=
1%. In contrast, languages like Arabic and Finnish had read/write accuracie=
s well above 80%. (Intriguingly, Marjou found that Chinese writing was more=
 lopsided. The bot could read Chinese with ease, but failed miserably at wr=
iting it.) In short, English may be the lingua franca, but only because it =
was the native tongue of two successive global empires (British and then Am=
erican). English is actually a dreadful language in which to become literat=
e.=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-k=
ids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#=
fnref4 )=0A=0AHow I came to (briefly) believe in whole-language teaching is=
 a somewhat embarrassing case study in how bad science spreads. When my dau=
ghter was around the age of four, the topic of reading instruction was on m=
y mind. As luck would have it, one day when I was substitute teaching at Le=
aside High School in Toronto, I was sitting in the staffroom and came upon =
a dusty book on reading instruction. Now, I have no recollection of the nam=
e of the book or its author. But it could have plausibly been Reading Witho=
ut Nonsense ( https://archive.org/details/readingwithoutno00smit ) , writte=
n by the psycholinguist Frank Smith ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_S=
mith_(psycholinguist) ) , one of the main architects of whole-language theo=
ry.=0A=0AAt any rate, the book made two arguments that, at the time, I foun=
d convincing. First, the author noted that when children are faced with an =
unfamiliar word, their first instinct is to guess at the word from the cont=
ext. Kids=E2=80=99 last instinct is to actually sound out the unknown word.=
 Second, the author noted that English phonics are a complicated mess, with=
 very few rules that are exception free. Hence teaching this mess, he argue=
d, is a waste of time. It=E2=80=99s better to focus on building kids=
=E2=80=99 bank of memorized words.=0A=0AWhat=E2=80=99s embarrassing is that=
 I found these arguments convincing, even though the author provided zero e=
vidence for the efficacy of his proposed approach. Let=E2=80=99s run throug=
h the problems.=0A=0AFirst up is the argument that kids avoid decoding word=
s. This observation is true, but is now recognized to be an avoidance tacti=
c. Decoding words is difficult, and so kids tend to avoid the task, especia=
lly if they=E2=80=99ve not been taught the principles to actually read the =
word in question.=0A=0ASecond, it is true that compared to languages like A=
rabic and Finnish, English is a phonological mess. But what scientists now =
recognize is that the complexity of English orthography means that more (no=
t less) time must be spent giving kids explicit and systematic phonics inst=
ruction.=0A=0AThird, the idea that memorizing words is easier than memorizi=
ng phonetics is pure silliness based on borderline innumeracy. A quick look=
 at structured literacy programs shows that they teach at most about 100 ph=
onological principles. In contrast, the English language contains at least =
460,000 words ( https://github.com/dwyl/english-words ) . So if you=
=E2=80=99re going to defend the wrote memorization of words, you=E2=80=
=99re defending a task that is 5,000 times more expansive.=0A=0ABack to my =
brief acceptance of these arguments. I found the whole-language approach co=
nvincing for understandable (but mistaken) reasons. The arguments sounded p=
lausible =E2=80=A6 from the standpoint of a literate adult who had long sin=
ce become unaware of his low-level decoding skills. Of course, when I tried=
 to put whole-language methods in action to teach my daughter, they failed =
badly. It was only in the face of this failure that I bothered to do some a=
ctually research, and learned the folly of my beliefs. (I discovered the sc=
ience of reading by googling the word =E2=80=98dyslexia=E2=80=99. That led =
me to Sally Shaywitz=E2=80=99s excellent book Overcoming Dyslexia ( https:/=
/www.dyslexia.yale.edu/research-science/overcoming-dyslexia/ ) , which lays=
 out the reasons why struggling readers need explicit phonics instruction.)=
=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kid=
s-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn=
ref5 )=0A=0AWhole-language methods became popular not just in the US, but a=
cross the anglophone world. For example, Timothy Mills reports ( https://ww=
w.ubplj.org/index.php/TBJE/article/view/1934 )  that a 2013 UK survey found=
 that a stunning =E2=80=9C89% of teachers believed that children needed to =
use a variety of cues to extract meaning from text=E2=80=9D.=E2=86=A9=
=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-get=
ting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fnref6 )=0A=
=0AMaking students repeat a grade is a controversial tactic because there i=
sn=E2=80=99t much evidence that it works. And one can see why. If a kid fai=
ls to read because they don=E2=80=99t understand the connection between sou=
nds and alphabetic symbols, forcing them through another year of the same f=
ailed instruction won=E2=80=99t help them. That said, it is wildly unethica=
l to let children proceed through school if they cannot read. Doing so sets=
 them up for a lifetime of failure. So is there a better alternative than m=
andatory retention?=0A=0APerhaps the most innovative approach comes from th=
e =E2=80=98Success for All=E2=80=99 program, described in Episode 12 ( http=
s://www.apmreports.org/episode/2025/02/27/sold-a-story-e12-the-evidence )  =
of the podcast Sold A Story ( https://features.apmreports.org/sold-a-story/=
 ) . In Success for All program, the entire school has a shared reading-ins=
truction block, in which students are grouped by reading ability and not by=
 grade. This ability-based streaming allows teachers to ramp up the interve=
ntion for kids who are falling behind. In short, the goal is to make it imp=
ossible for kids to fall behind in reading. I think the logic here is impec=
cable. Decoding skills must be mastery based. If kids do not get the basics=
 of decoding, everything else should be put on hold until they master this =
skill.=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/w=
hy-kids-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teachi=
ng/#fnref7 )=0A=0AWe can get a sense for the political nature of whole-lang=
uage theory by reading some of the later writings of whole-language theoris=
t Kenneth S. Goodman ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Goodman ) . In his=
 1998 book In defense of good teaching ( https://archive.org/details/indefe=
nseofgoodt0000unse ) , Goodman wastes no time arguing that phonics instruct=
ion is a far-right plot:=0A=0A> For well over half a century the far right =
has used a campaign for phonics to elect ultraconservative school board mem=
bers and attack both public education and teacher education.=0A>=0A=0AGoodm=
an is also keen to cast cognitive scientists as partisan hacks who are the =
enemy of good teachers:=0A=0A> Their =E2=80=9Ctrue science=E2=80=9D can pro=
duce =E2=80=9Cresearch-based programs.=E2=80=9D The far right can concentra=
te on keeping pressure on politicians and administrators at all levels, on =
being ready to pack a hearing room or school board meeting, while the disin=
formers and =E2=80=9Cscientists=E2=80=9D push the =E2=80=9Ctruth=E2=80=
=9D on teachers and administrators.=0A>=0A=0AOne gets the feeling that when=
 Goodman is faced with empirical evidence that contradicts whole-language t=
heory, he responds by vilifying scientists. It=E2=80=99s not a good look.=
=E2=86=A9=EF=B8=8E ( https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kid=
s-are-getting-worse-at-reading-the-case-against-whole-language-teaching/#fn=
ref8 )=0A=0AFurther reading=0A=0ABentz, C., & Dutkiewicz, E. (2026). Humans=
 40,000 y ago developed a system of conventional signs. Proceedings of the =
National Academy of Sciences, 123(9), e2520385123.=0A=0ABone, J. K., Bu, F.=
, Sonke, J. K., & Fancourt, D. (2025). The decline in reading for pleasure =
over 20 years of the American time use survey. Iscience, 28(9).=0A=0ACastle=
s, A., Rastle, K., & Nation, K. (2018). Ending the reading wars: Reading ac=
quisition from novice to expert. Psychological Science in the Public Intere=
st, 19(1), 5=E2=80=9351.=0A=0ADuff, D., Tomblin, J. B., & Catts, H. (2015).=
 The influence of reading on vocabulary growth: A case for a matthew effect=
. Journal of Speech, Language, and Hearing Research, 58(3), 853=E2=80=93864=
.=0A=0ALesnick, J., Goerge, R., Smithgall, C., & Gwynne, J. (2010). Reading=
 on grade level in third grade: How is it related to high school performanc=
e and college enrollment. Chicago, IL: Chapin Hall at the University of Chi=
cago, 1, 12.=0A=0AMarjou, X. (2021). OTEANN: Estimating the transparency of=
 orthographies with an artificial neural network. Proceedings of the Third =
Workshop on Computational Typology and Multilingual NLP, 1=E2=80=939.=0A=0A=
May, H., Blakeney, A., Shrestha, P., Mazal, M., & Kennedy, N. (2024). Long-=
term impacts of reading recovery through 3rd and 4th grade: A regression di=
scontinuity study. Journal of Research on Educational Effectiveness, 17(3),=
 433=E2=80=93458.=0A=0AMinus, M. A. E. (1993). The relationship of phonemic=
 awareness to reading level and the effects of phonemic awareness instructi=
on on the decoding skills of adult disabled readers. The University of Texa=
s at Austin.=0A=0AMoats, L. C. (2000). Whole language lives on: The illusio=
n of =E2=80=9Cbalanced=E2=80=9D reading instruction. Diane Publishing.=0A=
=0ARyan, H., & Goodman, D. (2016). Whole language and the fight for public =
education in the US. English in Education, 50(1), 60=E2=80=9371.=0A=0AShayw=
itz, S. (2003). Overcoming dyslexia. New York.=0A=0AAdd a comment to this p=
ost: https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/2026/03/28/why-kids-are-getting-wo=
