p;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; tex=
t-decoration: underline;">Sources and methods</a>]</figcaption></figure>=0A=
<h4 id=3D"whats-driving-the-reading-score-gap" style=3D"color: #2d3338; lin=
e-height: 1.2; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; margin: 48px 0 24px; lett=
er-spacing: -.02em; text-transform: uppercase;">What=E2=80=99s driving the =
reading-score gap?</h4>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">This concludes my tour=
 of the US read-score data. Let me summarize the main results. Over the las=
t three decades, high-school reading scores have declined, but in a non-uni=
form way. Over this period, the best high-school readers got better, while =
the worst readers got far worse. And perhaps most importantly, this widenin=
g reading-score gap persists across a variety of demographic groups =E2=80=
=94 groups which are well known to affect school outcomes. In short, someth=
ing is driving a wedge between the best and worst readers, and this driver =
is not captured by the federal survey data.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Now, it might seem tha=
t this lack of survey evidence leaves a world of possible causes. But then =
again, much is known about how and why kids fail at reading. Indeed, a <a t=
arget=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_=
content_redirect&amp;uuid=3Dfd0688cddfadee6c718de740b2b738669ef6643d5f015ee=
d8606b481e21f922d&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=
=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D80000a5451d7cf7063eb20=
8d7edc2cc6&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;=
encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9qb3VybmFscy5zYWdlcHViLmNvbS9kb2kvZnVsbC8xMC4xMTc3L=
zE1MjkxMDA2MTg3NzIyNzE&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" sty=
le=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">large body of research</=
a> shows that when kids struggle to read, it=E2=80=99s usually because they=
 were not taught the low-level skills that are required. And here, the crue=
l irony is that for the last three decades, many anglophone educators thoug=
ht it wise to <em>not</em> teach these skills. That=E2=80=99s because they =
were guided by the whole-language approach to teaching, which preached that=
 reading could be learned largely through exposure.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">We=E2=80=99ll get to t=
he spread of whole-language teaching in Part III. But first, we need some p=
rior knowledge. We need to understand how reading works, why it is hard to =
learn, and why it=E2=80=99s disastrous to not teach kids how to operate the=
 encryption algorithm.</p>=0A=
<h3 id=3D"part-ii-why-reading-is-hard-to-learn" style=3D"color: #2d3338; li=
ne-height: 1.2; font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 48px 0 24px;">Pa=
rt II: Why reading is hard to learn</h3>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">In literate cultures, =
writing is so ubiquitous that few people realize that it is a form of techn=
ology, and a miraculous one at that. Writing is an ingenious technique for =
encrypting spoken language into visual symbols =E2=80=94 symbols that can t=
hen be decrypted by another person.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">The advantages of writ=
ing over speaking are profound. A spoken sentence is gone the moment it is =
uttered. A written sentence can be preserved indefinitely. A spoken sentenc=
e requires a living speaker. A written sentence can be read long after the =
writer is dead, and in places the writer never imagined. In short, reading =
and writing come with many advantages over spoken language. But they also h=
ave one big downside, which is that compared to speaking, learning to read =
and write is far more difficult.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">There=E2=80=99s a reas=
on for this difficulty =E2=80=94 a reason that every grade-school teacher s=
hould have plastered on their wall. As the linguist Mark Liberman <a target=
=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_conte=
nt_redirect&amp;uuid=3De785ba631b91cb1d5776a9e7f18d04d1021d1278ef3670c690b8=
c9fbd2e14465&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D2592=
68523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3Dd22b320713805fb99c777e00c7660=
165&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded=
_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGluZy51cGVubi5lZHUvY291cnNlcy9GYWxsXzIwMDMvbGluZzAw=
MS9yZWFkaW5nX3dyaXRpbmcuaHRtbA=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d22=
7747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">observes</a>,=
 reading is hard to learn =E2=80=9C<em>for the same reasons that writing wa=
s hard to invent</em>=E2=80=9D. The lesson here is that each time a child s=
truggles to read, they are replicating, in shortened form, humanity=E2=80=
=99s lengthy struggle to invent the written word.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">To get a sense for thi=
s formative struggle, realize that humans developed spoken language as earl=
y as <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?actio=
n=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D2d08f126f010e95461755adcda24b8fd3371bc=
9915de84e325cb03ed8f429c99&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;=
user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D53304b9e7bf99d5=
7bf43f3a0b3cbb468&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.=
co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnJvbnRpZXJzaW4ub3JnL2pvdXJuYWxzL3BzeW=
Nob2xvZ3kvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMTAuMzM4OS9mcHN5Zy4yMDI1LjE1MDM5MDAvZnVsbA=3D&amp;ema=
il_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-dec=
oration: underline;">135,000 years ago</a>. Yet formal writing dates back a=
 mere <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?acti=
on=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D37b4a7c7452bb702b31cfe5f7310fc9a01807=
5f067de2ba7857d4c0c59c4a9e6&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp=
;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D08996cc4bcbf00=
2f99b996069f462670&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine=
.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvSGlzdG9yeV9vZ=
l93cml0aW5n&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color=
: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">5,000 years</a>. Now, I say =E2=80=
=98formal=E2=80=99 writing, because long before humans encoded words into a=
bstract symbols, we drew pictures that conveyed meaning. For example, more =
than 40,000 years ago, humans in present-day Spain drew a <a target=3D"_bla=
nk" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redir=
ect&amp;uuid=3D64e21a856144efd630d5f6895e9fb4af9fea491b64cb23ba8da78791354e=
8d54&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&am=
p;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3Dd667ba5e6816144cc7c195d2f9eb5858&amp;=
email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3Da=
HR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQ2F2ZV9vZl9FbF9DYXN0aWxsbw=3D&amp;em=
ail_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-de=
coration: underline;">picture of a bull</a> that is instantly recognizable =
to anyone today. It is with such pictures that <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D=
"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uui=
d=3D170d1d5a023a5fa58ea08767b6e426cc90dcebed1c7bd94dcf94bbf4b66edb1d&amp;bl=
og_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=
=3D754610508&amp;signature=3Da19864d50455e9fe73688b571a8b2647&amp;email_nam=
e=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly=
93d3cucG5hcy5vcmcvZG9pLzEwLjEwNzMvcG5hcy4yNTIwMzg1MTIz&amp;email_id=3D2ccc0=
18290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: unde=
rline;">writing begins</a>.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">For the first proto-wr=
iters, the most obvious way to encode meaning was to draw an image of the t=
hing they had in mind. To elicit the idea of a bull, they drew a bull. To e=
licit the idea of a snake, they drew a snake. And so on. Now, the intriguin=
g part is that even today, drawing pictures remains the most obvious way to=
 encode meaning.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">For example, if you sh=
ow a toddler a picture of a snake, they=E2=80=99ll happily shout =E2=80=98s=
nake=E2=80=99. Indeed, using this image-based method, a toddler will happil=
y decrypt the meaning of pictographs that are thousands of years old. (See =
Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_co=
ntent_redirect&amp;uuid=3D4d558f1195f8f697587d0e9bfdca198ab85e803de47c1d000=
eda70b7f6230b5c&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D2=
59268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D3cf8d44e2c5eb38575aee46f71=
8e3236&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;enco=
ded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93a=
Hkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hv=
bGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZpZy1oaWVyb2dseXBoaWNz&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018=
290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underl=
ine;">13</a> for some ancient Egyptian examples.<a target=3D"_blank" href=
=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;=
uuid=3D4dcdb152f1a9f5ccacdb2188dd0805d5b3c648c750effea0264729e3c207ebe6&amp=
;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_i=
d=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D4fdd74677aa8412b05a2736cc6950381&amp;email_na=
me=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6L=
y9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0=
dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGV=
hY2hpbmcvI2ZuMQ=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" class=
=3D"footnote-ref" id=3D"fnref1" role=3D"doc-noteref" style=3D"color: #3858e=
9; text-decoration: underline;"><sup>1</sup></a>) But note what the toddler=
 will <em>not</em> do. When shown the word =E2=80=98snake=E2=80=99, the tod=
dler will <em>not</em> shout =E2=80=98snake=E2=80=99. And they will not do =
so for the same reason that humans found it difficult to move from pictogra=
phs to more complex forms of writing. The path forward was not obvious.</p>=
=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;"><a id=3D"fig-hieroglyp=
hics" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;" href=3D"https:/=
/economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D5a3d=
df0302f50013c8ca2ea8c04edb4be7379e962573a32605f99931a56e9a8d&amp;blog_id=3D=
