re=3Ddcb117e35c4a1a42fb1d2becd20280fa&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_em=
ail=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG=
9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFka=
W5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZpZy1iZWxpZWY&=
amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; t=
ext-decoration: underline;">14</a>), we can use the rebus principle to enco=
de the English word =E2=80=98belief=E2=80=99. Clever!</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;"><a id=3D"fig-belief" s=
tyle=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;" href=3D"https://econom=
icsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D5a3ddf0302f=
50013c8ca2ea8c04edb4be7379e962573a32605f99931a56e9a8d&amp;blog_id=3D1609011=
25&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;=
signature=3D4d8a2a6bb935ba804d9babc4dd6f7e4e&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;=
user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url&amp;email_id=3D2ccc0182904982=
54a8f7ab6d227747ea"></a></p>=0A=
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large" style=3D"margin: 0 32px 24px;">=
<img src=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/=
belief.png" style=3D"border: none; -ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; max-wid=
th: 100%; margin-bottom: 24px;"><figcaption><strong>Figure 14: The rebus pr=
inciple =E2=80=94 using symbols to encode linguistic sounds.</strong> Lingu=
ists believe that the use of the rebus principle is a crucial step for the =
development of writing. With the rebus principle, one interprets images in =
terms of the linguistic sounds they represent (rather than the literal obje=
cts being displayed). In English, the symbols of a bee and a leaf can combi=
ne to represent the word =E2=80=98belief=E2=80=99.</figcaption></figure>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Now, to the modern (li=
terate) observer, the rebus principle seems both intuitive and obvious. Aft=
er all, it=E2=80=99s the principle that underpins how we read and write. (M=
ore on that in a moment.) And yet, for the first proto-writers, the rebus p=
rinciple was unintuitive. Why?</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Well, the problem seem=
s to be that for humans, speaking is so effortless that we have little know=
ledge of how we do it. Yes, we speak by making sounds =E2=80=A6 but it is t=
he <em>meaning</em> of these sounds that we say and hear. Indeed, we have a=
lmost no conscious knowledge of the sounds themselves. Or put another way, =
our brains naturally clump meaning into spoken units called =E2=80=98words=
=E2=80=99. But our brains find it quite foreign to consciously decompose th=
ese words into meaningless sounds. Yet the task for the first writers was t=
o do just that =E2=80=94 to reverse engineer what our brains do subconsciou=
sly. By all accounts, early writers found this task difficult. And to this =
day, children struggle to read largely because they struggle to decompose t=
he sounds within words.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">At any rate, once the =
rebus principle was discovered, it allowed writing systems to evolve in two=
 different ways. First, the symbols themselves tended to become more abstra=
ct with time. The effect of this abstraction was to simplify the act of wri=
ting, but to make learning how to read more difficult.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Second, the rebus prin=
ciple allowed writers to explore the phonetic level at which to encode thei=
r language. Here, we might think that alphabetic writing would be the most =
obvious path forward. But it was not. The alphabetic system was the <em>lea=
st</em> obvious approach to writing.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">To the oral speaker, t=
he natural unit of meaning is the individual word. Hence the most obvious w=
ay of writing was to equate symbols with whole words. This <a target=3D"_bl=
ank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redi=
rect&amp;uuid=3D0728a7668f1a5bf8f1daa4c314b7f5b0808a219ea4bf3daf7c75d61ed08=
be660&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&a=
mp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D3b3777887599c88700447df63d163787&amp=
;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3D=
aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTG9nb2dyYW0&amp;email_id=3D2ccc0182=
90498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underli=
ne;">=E2=80=98logographic=E2=80=99</a> system works perfectly well, and is =
the basis for Chinese writing.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">The next step down the=
 sound ladder is to use symbols to encode individual syllables. This <a tar=
get=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_co=
ntent_redirect&amp;uuid=3D5faa4d0545ebf819d90fdacdd6cda56289b30aca2cde24961=
48cb3bed8e787de&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D2=
59268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D1bedb0037dbb773feb60fb06e7=
e4b318&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;enco=
ded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvU3lsbGFiYXJ5&amp;email_id=
=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decorati=
on: underline;">=E2=80=98syllabic=E2=80=99</a> approach is the basis for Ja=
panese writing.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Finally, the lowest st=
ep down the sound ladder is to use symbols (an alphabet) to encode individu=
al <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=
=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3Db70908b7ae9c4e0a6c53efa978dd73ead526982=
de2381f774917e1f6ad599c91&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;u=
ser_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D18051f40979b80de=
dd383c92caddfc01&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.c=
o&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUGhvbmVtZQ=3D&a=
mp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; te=
xt-decoration: underline;">=E2=80=98phonemes=E2=80=99</a>, which are the sm=
allest unit of linguistic sound. The advantage of this =E2=80=98alphabetic=
=E2=80=99 approach is that it is by far the most efficient encoding method,=
 requiring the user to memorize the least number of symbols. <a target=3D"_=
blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_re=
direct&amp;uuid=3D36c039b21acee62b4e27ce3b0249b34936db9d93da4683b3965650a3b=
d5c18cf&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523=
&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D30f6595a8502856ee39b4c8bb2c19a5d&a=
mp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=
=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lk=
cy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGF=
uZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZuMg=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d22774=
7ea" class=3D"footnote-ref" id=3D"fnref2" role=3D"doc-noteref" style=3D"col=
or: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;"><sup>2</sup></a> However, the dis=
advantage, as Mark Liberman <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsf=
romthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3De785ba631b91cb1=
d5776a9e7f18d04d1021d1278ef3670c690b8c9fbd2e14465&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&a=
mp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;sign=
ature=3Dd22b320713805fb99c777e00c7660165&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user=
_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGluZy51cGVubi5=
lZHUvY291cnNlcy9GYWxsXzIwMDMvbGluZzAwMS9yZWFkaW5nX3dyaXRpbmcuaHRtbA=3D&amp;=
email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-=
decoration: underline;">observes</a>, is that alphabetic writing places a =
=E2=80=9Cspecial burden=E2=80=9D on the reader, since it requires that they=
 gain conscious access to the lowest unit of linguistic sound =E2=80=94 a u=
nit that is =E2=80=9Crelatively inaccessible to introspective scrutiny=E2=
=80=9D.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">It is likely because o=
f this =E2=80=9Cspecial burden=E2=80=9D that whereas logographic and syllab=
ic forms of writing evolved multiple times in different places, alphabetic =
writing seems to have <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthe=
topdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D2d6bccdb7049e3d72bba7=
a3dd667fa00a3bd09b523778226f7b829c2627dba90&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;pos=
t_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=
=3Db4461fdcb0176bb55659a9d5b24251a2&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_emai=
l=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dp=
a2kvSGlzdG9yeV9vZl90aGVfYWxwaGFiZXQ&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d=
227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">evolved onl=
y once</a>. It arose out of the <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://econom=
icsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3Dbb9af987d46=
2927e613cffac1d2473452aa452510772d9fc0832d9458b110cd8&amp;blog_id=3D1609011=
25&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;=
signature=3D0eff32aca5a280d3b15dba0d951d8647&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;=
user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWE=
ub3JnL3dpa2kvUHJvdG8tU2luYWl0aWNfc2NyaXB0&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8=
f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">Semit=
ic tradition</a>, which developed a consonant-only system of writing. When =
the ancient Greeks later borrowed these symbols, they adapted some of the l=
etters to notate vowels. All modern alphabets seem to have sprung from this=
 singular lineage.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">The point is that when=
 children struggle to read alphabetic writing, they are in good company. Al=
phabetic writing is the least obvious way to store linguistic meaning. And =
it is also the writing method that is most susceptible to <em>corruption</e=
m>.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">For example, in modern=
 English, there are nine different ways to encode the long =E2=80=98a=E2=80=
=99 sound (as in halo, aid, ate, say, they, rein, great, eight, and straigh=
t). Who invented this absurd system? No one did. These different notations =
evolved from older phonetic principles that have since been corrupted, as p=
ronunciation changed but spelling did not. Thus, English is littered with s=
ilent letters that were once pronounced (as in =E2=80=98knight=E2=80=99), h=
omonyms that once had distinct pronunciations (as in =E2=80=98meat=E2=80=99=
 and =E2=80=9Cmeet=E2=80=9D), and a myriad of ways to spell the same sound.=
<a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Du=
ser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3De2d41c8cc6973de34436443f3edb355d9a4fc2eb4ec=
7bfdb3cca27d724f07b61&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_=
id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D07acaf527fa56f795707=
6b7b81105700&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&am=
p;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8=
yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3=
Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZuMw=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254=
a8f7ab6d227747ea" class=3D"footnote-ref" id=3D"fnref3" role=3D"doc-noteref"=
 style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;"><sup>3</sup></a></p>=
=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">No one would design su=
ch a convoluted system by choice. And yet, it is the system that English ch=
ildren must learn. We fool ourselves if we think it is easy or =E2=80=98nat=
ural=E2=80=99.<a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.=
com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D07e536941879c1e23dfa4102fc2c2=
45d70f8dd4cfe601e9dd16a40c843e52b9b&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D1=
4975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3Db79990=
bfa96d8ff77339ded0e7b82f56&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@=
woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb=
20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1j=
YXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZuNA=3D&amp;email_id=3D2c=
cc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" class=3D"footnote-ref" id=3D"fnref4" role=
=3D"doc-noteref" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;"><sup=
>4</sup></a> And we doubly fool ourselves if we think that children can ded=
uce the principles behind English phonetic encoding without explicit instru=
ction.</p>=0A=
<h4 id=3D"hiding-the-decryption-key" style=3D"color: #2d3338; line-height: =
1.2; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; margin: 48px 0 24px; letter-spacing=
: -.02em; text-transform: uppercase;">Hiding the decryption key</h4>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">To summarize our foray=
 into the history of writing, reading is difficult to learn because it requ=
ires developing a set of low-level skills that are not intuitive or natural=
 to the oral speaker.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Now, the tyranny is th=
at for a good reader, these low-level skills have become so automatic that =
they are subconscious. Hence, a good reader might think it reasonable to te=
ach a child to read without giving explicit instruction on the principles i=
nvolved. This form of teaching is a strikingly bad idea; and yet it is the =
method that dominates anglophone schooling.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">More on that in a mome=
nt. But first, let me convince you (a good reader) that you have a set of l=
ow-level decoding skills that are largely subconscious. Go ahead and read t=
he following words aloud:</p>=0A=
<div style=3D"margin-bottom: 24px; text-align: center;">=0A=
</div>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">As you read, you no do=
ubt realized that these are not English words. They are <em>pseudowords</em=
> that are assembled using the principles of English phonetics. (You can ge=
nerate more pseudowords <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromt=
hetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D84a415a94ba98656933=
6ac81b49d3506a38c67f1cffd4b8d8735918d9e18e587&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;p=
ost_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signatur=
e=3D52d7cc8c9b476f886c446f21962ad23b&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_ema=
il=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9yYW5kb213b3JkZ2VuZXJhdG9=
yLmNvbS9mYWtlLXdvcmQucGhw&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" =
style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">here</a>.)</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">The purpose of these p=
seudowords is to illustrate that good readers have internalized the low-lev=
el principles behind English phonetic encoding. Good readers understand how=
 letters combine to represent sounds, and how these sounds can be combined =
into words (real or not). Of course, the corollary is that bad readers lack=
 these low-level skills. Which is why, when faced with pseudowords, bad rea=
ders fall flat on their face.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">With this failure in m=
ind, here is the trick to bad reading instruction: ask students to read wit=
hout teaching them the decryption key.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;"><img src=3D"https://ec=
onomicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/divider.png" width=3D"=
120" style=3D"border: none; -ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; max-width: 100=
%; margin-bottom: 24px; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: au=
to;"></p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">To describe a lesson i=
n bad reading instruction, it seems only fair to use myself as an example. =
When my daughter started school, she was enrolled in French immersion, whic=
h meant that she=E2=80=99d learn to read French at school and English at ho=
me. Her home-school teacher would be me =E2=80=A6 Blair Fix, PhD &amp; VGR =
(very good reader).</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Now, at the time, I=E2=
=80=99d bought into the whole-language approach to reading instruction.<a t=
arget=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_=
content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D431ff27d69423d52ccc0811ac723e99084eb075bb59d062=
ba0247b3f771bd9ee&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=
=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D1ce19c7594ab732003a08a=
a405db27de&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;=
encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yO=
C93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qt=
d2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmcvI2ZuNQ=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8=
f7ab6d227747ea" class=3D"footnote-ref" id=3D"fnref5" role=3D"doc-noteref" s=
tyle=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;"><sup>5</sup></a> Forge=
t phonics, I thought. We=E2=80=99ll just start reading together, and my dau=
ghter will naturally pick things up. But she didn=E2=80=99t. So with the be=
nefit of hindsight, let me illustrate how things went wrong.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Our first step was to =
read simple picture books like the one shown in Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"http=
s://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D3=
21796edf2f6f8d0f3f891d9d50ada0ee3bff0846b144789794bbaa1ba15b925&amp;blog_id=
=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D7546=
10508&amp;signature=3D5fb81cd83df069b5a6f0587fcf56bf4f&amp;email_name=3Dnew=
-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub=
21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13=
b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmc=
vI2ZpZy1hcHBsZQ=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=
=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">15</a>. These books are ca=
lled =E2=80=98levelled readers=E2=80=99, and they=E2=80=99re meant to be co=
-read, with prompts from the pictures. First, I=E2=80=99d read the book. Th=
en my daughter would =E2=80=98read=E2=80=99 it back to me. Things seemed to=
 be going well =E2=80=A6 or so I thought.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;"><a id=3D"fig-apple" st=
yle=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;" href=3D"https://economi=
csfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D5a3ddf0302f5=
0013c8ca2ea8c04edb4be7379e962573a32605f99931a56e9a8d&amp;blog_id=3D16090112=
5&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;s=
ignature=3D4d8a2a6bb935ba804d9babc4dd6f7e4e&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;u=
ser_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url&amp;email_id=3D2ccc01829049825=
4a8f7ab6d227747ea"></a></p>=0A=
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large" style=3D"margin: 0 32px 24px;">=
<img src=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/=
apples_red_crop.png" style=3D"border: none; -ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic=
; max-width: 100%; margin-bottom: 24px;"><figcaption><strong>Figure 15: Tea=
ching children how to avoid reading.</strong> This is an excerpt from the b=
ook <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=
=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3Dd579b627fed86df23f4edd01138ec2105d32bd3=
7be73e34a017f8d4197b13edc&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;u=
ser_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D8e8a6d019bcd3295=
9c35155dd832fa53&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.c=
o&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9hcmNoaXZlLm9yZy9kZXRhaWxzL2ZpcnN0bGl0dGxlcmV=
hZGVyc3doYXRpc3JlZA=3D&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" sty=
le=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;"><em>First Little Readers=
 =E2=80=93 What Is Red?</em></a> It is typical of the levelled-reader forma=
t. Note the repetitive sentence structure, which can be easily memorized an=
d recited based on cues from the pictures. Note also the difficulty of the =
actual decoding task. In this supposed =E2=80=98Level A=E2=80=99 reader, ki=
ds are asked to decode the words =E2=80=98apples=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98stra=
wberries=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 words that are phonetically complicated. In sho=
rt, this book practically begs children to <em>not</em> read the text, and =
to instead recite the message from pictographic cues.</figcaption></figure>=
=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">What I realize now is =
that these levelled readers actually teach children how to <em>avoid</em> r=
eading. Again, the history of writing is instructive as to why. To develop =
alphabet writing, people had to realize that linguistic meaning (i.e.&nbsp;=
words) could be broken down into sounds, and that these sounds could be enc=
oded into symbols:</p>=0A=
<div style=3D"margin-bottom: 24px; text-align: center;">=0A=
</div>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Learning to read there=
fore involves the reverse operation. The learner must take symbols, map the=
m onto sounds, and decode the meaning:</p>=0A=
<div style=3D"margin-bottom: 24px; text-align: center;">=0A=
</div>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Looking at levelled re=
aders, these books make no attempt to teach the reading decryption algorith=
m. Instead, they take a repetitive sentence structure and map it onto a set=
 of richly illustrated images. Of course, kids love this format, because it=
 provides a far more obvious path for encoding meaning. Indeed, it is the s=
ame path taken by the first writers, who took meaning and mapped it onto pi=
ctures:</p>=0A=
<div style=3D"margin-bottom: 24px; text-align: center;">=0A=
</div>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">When we ask a child to=
 =E2=80=98read=E2=80=99 an illustrated (levelled) reader, they naturally ta=
ke the easiest path by decoding the message from the picture:</p>=0A=
<div style=3D"margin-bottom: 24px; text-align: center;">=0A=
</div>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Now, the problem here =
is that asking a child to decode meaning from pictures actively misleads th=
em about how reading actually works. Historically, the path from pictograph=
s to alphabetic writing was long and torturous. Indeed, the path was so dif=
ficult that it happened only once. Hence, it is completely unreasonable to =
request that a child use pictographs as a tool for deducing alphabetic prin=
ciples. Many children will not make this conceptual leap.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Instead, when children=
 are shown pictographs with associated text, what tends to happen is that t=
hey memorize a few of the simpler looking words, and then they recite (or s=
imply guess) the rest of the words from the context (which includes the pic=
ture and the repetitive sentence structure). Unsurprisingly, researchers ha=
ve observed this guessing behavior countless times. The strategy occurs bec=
ause actually reading the words on the page is the hardest and least intuit=
ive option for decoding meaning. Guessing the message from the pictures and=
 the context is far easier. And so that=E2=80=99s what kids do.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">With word guessing in =
mind, here is where things get weird. When whole-language theorists observe=
d children=E2=80=99s guessing tactic, they interpreted it as a <em>learning=
 strategy</em>. Indeed, they enshrined it in a pedagogical approach called =
the <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=
=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D66871dcb8753b9d4f3f8c46c0b0e0d63968addf=
50860da2c9e29f338b5d1fe1e&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;u=
ser_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3Df85a28807bbaeab6=
86ba97cd51f07c0f&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.c=
o&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvVGhyZWVfY3VlaW5=
n&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9;=
 text-decoration: underline;">=E2=80=98cueing method=E2=80=99</a>, in which=
 children are taught to read text by looking first to the picture, next to =
the syntactic context, and last to the actual word.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">In short, the whole-la=
nguage method took a reading avoidance tactic (guessing words from context)=
 and transformed it into a =E2=80=98strategy=E2=80=99 for learning how to r=
ead. As you might guess, the effect of this strategy is to leave the worst =
readers behind.</p>=0A=
<h4 id=3D"teaching-the-decryption-key" style=3D"color: #2d3338; line-height=
: 1.2; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; margin: 48px 0 24px; letter-spaci=
ng: -.02em; text-transform: uppercase;">Teaching the decryption key</h4>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">The irony of whole-lan=
guage pedagogy is that when it swept through anglophone schools in the 1980=
s and 1990s, cognitive scientists were <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https:/=
/economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3Dbdf3=
7558e55212ebeabfaf03010ea1f524b392c38f0343741df1b29db5d6d730&amp;blog_id=3D=
160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D7546105=
08&amp;signature=3D52406697cac538b4ba88723963fc6ba7&amp;email_name=3Dnew-po=
st&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lcmljLmVk=
Lmdvdi8/aWQ9RUQ0MzAzNjY&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" st=
yle=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">codifying</a> the best =
practices in reading instruction. Suffice it to say that these best practic=
es are <em>not</em> what whole-language theory preaches.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">In a nutshell, cogniti=
ve scientists discovered that kids struggle to read for the same reason tha=
t humans struggled to develop writing. For the oral speaker, it is unnatura=
l to decompose words into sounds. Hence, kids who struggle to read typicall=
y lack =E2=80=98phonemic awareness=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 they do not hear the =
sounds within words. And so the solution is to <em>teach</em> this skill. T=
each kids that English words are built from a repertoire of <a target=3D"_b=
lank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_red=
irect&amp;uuid=3D98a4c693d9403a2128c34f1b38aba57fb08f78b13f948236929e199d91=
3c72e0&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&=
amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3D409b7852329bef520c5cabcf77712641&am=
p;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=
=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRW5nbGlzaF9waG9ub2xvZ3k&amp;emai=
l_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-deco=
ration: underline;">several dozen sounds</a>. Teach kids how to segment wor=
ds into sounds. Teach kids how sounds map onto the alphabet. Yes, this inst=
ruction is low-level work. But for young children, it is exciting new knowl=
edge. They love it!</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Once kids grasp the ba=
sics of how the alphabet represents sounds, they=E2=80=99re ready to read t=
hree-letter words like =E2=80=98sit=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98hat=E2=80=99. Nex=
t, they can read these words in simple sentences. Crucially, the practice r=
eading must lack picture cues, because pictures provide a way to avoid the =
cognitively demanding task of decoding words. (Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https=
://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D8e=
0fae8e0454cf2abd9156c1a631e6011f6b4c309c2e3f68aab6aa1a298acf91&amp;blog_id=
=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D7546=
10508&amp;signature=3D8b92f86d064bdbaa4f3e64225de3d143&amp;email_name=3Dnew=
-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly9lY29ub=
21pY3Nmcm9tdGhldG9wZG93bi5jb20vMjAyNi8wMy8yOC93aHkta2lkcy1hcmUtZ2V0dGluZy13=
b3JzZS1hdC1yZWFkaW5nLXRoZS1jYXNlLWFnYWluc3Qtd2hvbGUtbGFuZ3VhZ2UtdGVhY2hpbmc=
vI2ZpZy10aHI&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"colo=
r: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">16</a> shows a sample reading task=
 from <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?acti=
on=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D886149ef1a7f81266fa499825e2c3c5f0185e=
11c984e80500b6602fe5063bc7f&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&amp;post_id=3D14975&amp=
;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;signature=3De5297fe0d2d8a3=
09fd46697d9ce678c1&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;user_email=3Dinfo@woodfine=
.co&amp;encoded_url=3DaHR0cHM6Ly90cmVhc3VyZWh1bnQucHJlbmRhLmNvL2hlbHBmdWwtY=
WR1bHRz&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a8f7ab6d227747ea" style=3D"color: #3=
858e9; text-decoration: underline;">Treasure Hunt Reading</a>, a free struc=
tured literacy program.)</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;"><a id=3D"fig-thr" styl=
e=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;" href=3D"https://economics=
fromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D5a3ddf0302f500=
13c8ca2ea8c04edb4be7379e962573a32605f99931a56e9a8d&amp;blog_id=3D160901125&=
amp;post_id=3D14975&amp;user_id=3D259268523&amp;subs_id=3D754610508&amp;sig=
nature=3D4d8a2a6bb935ba804d9babc4dd6f7e4e&amp;email_name=3Dnew-post&amp;use=
r_email=3Dinfo@woodfine.co&amp;encoded_url&amp;email_id=3D2ccc018290498254a=
8f7ab6d227747ea"></a></p>=0A=
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large" style=3D"margin: 0 32px 24px;">=
<img src=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/=
thr.png" style=3D"border: none; -ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; max-width:=
 100%; margin-bottom: 24px;"><figcaption><strong>Figure 16: A typical readi=
ng task in a structured literacy program.</strong> In this example from <a =
target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://economicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser=
