7747ea" style=3D"color: #3858e9; text-decoration: underline;">460,000 words=
</a>. So if you=E2=80=99re going to defend the wrote memorization of words,=
 you=E2=80=99re defending a task that is 5,000 times more expansive.</p>=0A=
<p style=3D"font-family: -apple-system,system-ui,blinkmacsystemfont,&quot;S=
egoe UI&quot;,Roboto,Oxygen-Sans,Ubuntu,Cantarell,&quot;Helvetica Neue&quot=
;,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 400; margin: 0; line-height: 1.=
7; padding: 0; color: #101517; margin-bottom: 24px;">Back to my brief accep=
tance of these arguments. I found the whole-language approach convincing fo=
r understandable (but mistaken) reasons. The arguments sounded plausible =
=E2=80=A6 from the standpoint of a literate adult who had long since become=
 unaware of his low-level decoding skills. Of course, when I tried to put w=
hole-language methods in action to teach my daughter, they failed badly. It=
 was only in the face of this failure that I bothered to do some actually r=
esearch, and learned the folly of my beliefs. (I discovered the science of =
reading by googling the word =E2=80=98dyslexia=E2=80=99. That led me to Sal=
ly Shaywitz=E2=80=99s excellent book <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://e=
conomicsfromthetopdown.com?action=3Duser_content_redirect&amp;uuid=3D1c5e88=
